WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.040
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger, and&nbsp;
we're establishing proper foundations for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:19.590
geometry. Today's lecture is a very important one&nbsp;
because we make the transition from 20th-century&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.590 --> 00:00:27.060
geometry to 21st-century geometry. We do that by&nbsp;
introducing a better form of measurement than that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:34.650
is classically used, one that actually goes back&nbsp;
to ancient Greece. We also establish the two most&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.650 --> 00:00:41.280
important theorems in all of mathematics. So I&nbsp;
remind you that up till now we've been talking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:47.280
about points and lines. A point for us is an&nbsp;
ordered pair of rational numbers. We are working&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.280 --> 00:00:56.220
only over the rational number field. A line is&nbsp;
a proportion of three rational numbers, and we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.220 --> 00:01:03.210
say that the point A lies on the line L precisely&nbsp;
when a times x plus b times y plus c equals zero.

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:10.770
Now we want to establish an idea of separation&nbsp;
between points. We have two points: how do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:19.140
we measure how far those points are apart? The&nbsp;
traditional answer is distance, but as we've seen,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.140 --> 00:01:25.590
Euclid does not use distance, and we're not going&nbsp;
to either. We're going to use something more akin&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.590 --> 00:01:32.130
to what the ancient Greeks did: the notion of&nbsp;
quadrants. The quadrants between two points a1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:32.130 --> 00:01:37.920
and a2 is given by this simple formula: the&nbsp;
difference between the x-coordinates squared&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:45.630
plus the difference in the y-coordinates squared.&nbsp;
That ensures that it's always a rational number;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.630 --> 00:01:52.800
there are no square roots that we're taking,&nbsp;
so we stay inside the domain in which we work.

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:59.490
Some obvious properties: first of all, it's&nbsp;
symmetric; if you change the a1 and a2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.490 --> 00:02:06.000
the quadrants does not change. Secondly,&nbsp;
the quadrants is zero precisely when the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:11.010
two points are actually the same because if&nbsp;
this squared plus this squared equals zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.010 --> 00:02:16.400
then this must be zero and this&nbsp;
must be zero as well. Finally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:20.660
the quadrants is always a positive number&nbsp;
because squares are always positive.

00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:30.380
So in our mind, a point is really an object in&nbsp;
the coordinate plane. For example, the point (2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.380 --> 00:02:35.570
1) really represents, in our mind, this point&nbsp;
here with x-coordinate 2 and y-coordinate 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.570 --> 00:02:42.440
and the point B with coordinates (6, 2) represents&nbsp;
this point here. What's the quadrants between A&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:48.890
and B? Well, by definition, it's the difference&nbsp;
between the x-coordinates squared plus the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:55.250
difference between the y-coordinates squared&nbsp;
for a total of 17. And what is the meaning of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.250 --> 00:03:02.510
that geometrically? It has a very simple&nbsp;
meaning: the quadrants is just the area&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:08.780
of the square built on that segment. That's&nbsp;
exactly the kind of quantity that the ancient&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.780 --> 00:03:17.990
Greeks used in their understanding of geometry.&nbsp;
Moreover, this quantity can be calculated without&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.990 --> 00:03:27.500
any irrational numbers because we can subdivide&nbsp;
this square into pieces whose areas we can count.

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:34.790
C, D, and E are three collinear points.&nbsp;
The three quadrants formed by them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.790 --> 00:03:42.110
you can calculate easily, are 10, 40, and 90. So&nbsp;
that quadrants is 10, that quadrants is 40, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.110 --> 00:03:49.190
that quadrants is 90. An absolutely fundamental&nbsp;
question is: what is the relationship between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.190 --> 00:03:55.370
these three numbers? The other important problem&nbsp;
is when we have a right triangle like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.370 --> 00:04:03.560
where this line and this line are perpendicular.&nbsp;
You can calculate that the quadrants here are 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:11.420
20, and 25. I think you probably all know what&nbsp;
the relationship between these three numbers is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:17.180
but the relationship between these three&nbsp;
numbers is almost as important historically.

00:04:17.180 --> 00:04:22.460
Pythagoras' theorem comes first, so let's look&nbsp;
at that one first. We have three points a1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.460 --> 00:04:29.310
a2, and a3, and in general, we'll use the&nbsp;
notation that q1 represents the quadrants&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:34.110
between a2 and a3, q2 represents&nbsp;
the quadrants between a1 and a3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.110 --> 00:04:43.410
and q3 represents the quadrants between a1 and&nbsp;
a2. Then Pythagoras' theorem states that a1a3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.410 --> 00:04:50.400
which is the line through these two points, is&nbsp;
perpendicular to a2a3, the line between these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.400 --> 00:05:00.600
two points, precisely when this relation between&nbsp;
the quadrants holds: q3 equals q1 plus q2. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:09.240
this is the way Euclid stated the theorem as well.&nbsp;
He did not state it in terms of distances squared;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.240 --> 00:05:14.550
he stated it in terms of areas of squares,&nbsp;
which is exactly what these quadrants&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.550 --> 00:05:22.650
represent. So this is a more modern but also&nbsp;
more ancient form of this most important theory.

00:05:22.650 --> 00:05:30.120
Now let's have a look at a proof. We'll suppose&nbsp;
that a1, a2, and a3 have coordinates x1, y1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:38.850
x2, y2, x3, y3. Now we've already established a&nbsp;
theorem that tells us what the line is joining&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.850 --> 00:05:46.440
two points, so here's the line between a1 and a3,&nbsp;
and here's the line joining a2 and a3 in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:54.030
the coordinates. We also know by definition what&nbsp;
it means for these two lines to be perpendicular.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.030 --> 00:06:04.200
They're perpendicular precisely when this times&nbsp;
this plus this times this equals zero. Now let's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:11.130
have a look at the right-hand side up here: we&nbsp;
have q3 equals q1 plus q2, so let's look at q1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.130 --> 00:06:23.220
plus q2 minus q3. There's q1, there's q2, and then&nbsp;
we've subtracted q3, and when you work that out,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:29.430
you expand it all out, you have a good look at&nbsp;
it, and then you can verify that what you end&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:35.310
up getting is two times this expression. Now what&nbsp;
is this expression? It's exactly the expression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.310 --> 00:06:42.630
that occurred up here. So when this expression is&nbsp;
zero, then this expression is zero, meaning that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.630 --> 00:06:48.510
q1 plus q2 equals q3, and conversely, when this&nbsp;
expression is zero, then this expression is zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.290 --> 00:06:55.860
meaning that the two lines are perpendicular. This&nbsp;
is a completely algebraic proof of Pythagoras'&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.860 --> 00:07:02.580
theorem. It doesn't involve any pictures; it is&nbsp;
therefore more powerful than any proof involving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.580 --> 00:07:09.510
pictures. It extends, in other words, to many&nbsp;
other situations and other fields as well.

00:07:09.510 --> 00:07:16.230
Now let's have a look at the other crucial&nbsp;
and important result. Here is the second&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.230 --> 00:07:20.850
most important theorem in mathematics.&nbsp;
It's called the triple quad formula,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.850 --> 00:07:27.780
and using exactly the same notation as we've&nbsp;
had, the line a1a3 is parallel to the line&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.780 --> 00:07:38.850
a2a3 precisely when this relation holds: q3 minus&nbsp;
q1 minus q2 all squared equals 4 times q1 times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.850 --> 00:07:45.630
q2. That's more complicated than Pythagoras'&nbsp;
theorem, and it's perhaps no surprise that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.630 --> 00:07:52.140
Euclid did not discover this theorem. Here's&nbsp;
a proof, or at least an outline of a proof:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:52.140 --> 00:08:01.380
these two lines are parallel precisely when the&nbsp;
three points are collinear. In our previous video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:08.790
we've established when three points are collinear.&nbsp;
It comes down to this expression being zero in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.790 --> 00:08:14.490
coordinates of the points. Now let's look at the&nbsp;
difference between the left and the right-hand&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.490 --> 00:08:19.890
side. There's the right-hand side minus the&nbsp;
left-hand side; that's an expression involving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:19.890 --> 00:08:28.320
lots of q1s, q2s, x1s, and y2s, and so on.&nbsp;
When you substitute that in, expand it all out,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:35.910
then a remarkable factorization appears. You&nbsp;
end up getting 4 times this quantity squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.910 --> 00:08:43.680
and this quantity that's appearing here is&nbsp;
exactly the same as this quantity. So this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.680 --> 00:08:49.110
being zero implies that this equals zero, and&nbsp;
this being zero implies that this equals zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:55.920
In other words, the three points are collinear&nbsp;
precisely when this algebraic relation holds.

00:08:55.920 --> 00:09:05.190
This is a very important result, and with&nbsp;
Pythagoras' theorem, these are the two main&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.190 --> 00:09:12.000
pillars of metrical geometry in the plane.&nbsp;
This is all described at some length in my&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:18.480
YouTube series called "WildTrig on Rational&nbsp;
Trigonometry," which I strongly suggest that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.480 --> 00:09:25.710
you have a look at. Next time we're going to&nbsp;
look at the separation between two lines and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.710 --> 00:09:32.640
introduce the important idea of a spread. I hope&nbsp;
you'll join me for that. I'm Norman Wildberger.

